Sometimes, you may want to reference other papers within the authors list. For example, if a paper has been published in a conference with proceedings, there might be a longer version of the same paper in a journal. To indicate this, you might add "[J]" or "[CONF]" after the author's name. To do that with \usepackage{hyperref}, add an optional argument to \cite:

\begin{code}
\cite[J]{my-long-paper}
\end{code}

This will output:

\textbf{\large{My long paper}}

To make it look like a footnote, use the optional argument to \footnote:

\begin{code}
\footnotemark[J]
           {\textbf{\Large{My long paper}}}
\end{code}

This will output:

\textbf{\large{My long paper}}

Note that I have left out the space before the `]` at the end of the footnote text. This is because, when using \footnote, a space is automatically added at the end of the footnote text and before the reference.

